1 Learning Outcomes

  • Use Branching in Git to evolve your code without risking the master branch
    • Create new branches, update files, push to GitHub, and merge updates to the master
  • Differentiate between Forking and Cloning
  • Differentiate between Models for Team Work flow
    • Shared Repository
    • Fork and Pull
  • Use Merge command and Pull Requests for coordinated development
  • Apply a GitHub workflow model to Group project

1.1 References

  • GitHub Flow
  • Git Help

2 Motivation for Branching and Team/Project Work Flow

  • You can use basic Git for configuration management
    • Single repositories with single branches
    • Edit the code base to develop new changes, Add and Commit
    • Push to GitHub for cloud-based replication and sharing
  • Git has additional capabilities to enable new development without disturbing the master code baseline
  • Git’s support for Branching allows users to make multiple changes to the code and test it prior to incorporating the new code into the master branch code baseline
    • Supports best practices for clear separation between Develop - Test - Production/Deployed processes
    • Lower risk for production code
    • Allows Parallel development of multiple features
  • Branching leads naturally to support for Team/Project Development
  • GitHub has two common workflow models for teams
    • Shared Repository Model
    • Fork and Pull Model
  • Choosing a workflow model allows for consistent, efficient parallel development by teams while minimizing risk to the deployed production code or the working master code base.

3 Branching using Git

  • Note: Git 2.23, released on 16 August 2019, added two experimental commands: git switch and git restore to augment and simplify the use of git checkout so older posts may refer to git checkout instead of what you see below.

3.1 Creating a New Branch

  • Every repo has at least one Branch - the Master branch

  • The Master is considered sacrosanct - it is the baseline or production version of code - it is known to work.

  • Branching is the Git functionality which allows you to add new branches (for additional analysis or code features) and then eventually merge them into your master branch to create a new baseline master version.

  • The repo is a collection of snapshots of your code that allow you to go back in time

  • Creating a branch creates a new, additional, set of snapshots that does not affect the master branch snapshots.

  • Before you create a new branch:

  1. Ensure your master is up to date with the remote master repo using git pull
    • You may have made changes to the master from a different branch.
    • git pull runs git fetch followed by git merge
    • If there are conflicts, you will have to resolve them and try again until you get a clean pull
    • GitHub documentation and Google/Stack Overflow can be your friend
  2. Check for existing branches with git branch -a. It may return something like:
    * master remotes/origin/master

  • The * master means the master branch is the current working branch

  • remotes/origin.master means the remote repo on GitHub also has one branch and it is called master as well.

  • Create a new local branch with git branch new_branch_name and call it “testname”

    • The new_branch_name should be short but descriptive of the contents of the branch
    • Local guidelines may ask you to tie the name to a code issue, a specification, or bug report ID
    • Make sure you have committed any changes before switching to a new branch so your master is up to date.
    • Close any open files before switching to a new branch
    • if you run git branch -a now after creating the branch called testname you will get:
      * master testname remotes/origin/master
    • note the * has stayed on master

3.2 Working within a Branch

  1. Change to any branch with git switch branch_name
  • This moves you to the new branch (or an existing branch of that name)
  • It also changes the structure in the R Studio Files since you are now working on a new branch.
  • If you run git branch a now after creating a branch called testname you will get:
    master * testname remotes/origin/master
  • Note the * has moved to testname which is now your “working directory”
  • If you have an open file that exists in the branch, it will switch to that version of the file.
  • If you have an open file that does not exist in the new branch, R Studio will ask you to close it since the directory “no longer exists” - you are on a different branch.
  1. Ensure your branch is up to date with the master with git merge origin/master
  • This will update your current branch with any code changes (perhaps from other branches) from the local master branch.
  • If you have an open file it will update it with any changes from the master file.
  1. Update your analysis/code files as desired. Remember to save, add, and commit as usual.

  • Only now your updates are going into snapshots for the branch

  • For the exercise, add some additional commentary on the graph and save the file - but don’t close it.

  • For the exercise, delete the html file.

  • Running git status may show something like the following:

    On branch testname
    Changes not staged for commit:
    (use "git add <file>..." to update what will be committed)
    (use "git restore <file>..." to discard changes in working directory)
    modified: 98_github_team_workflow/98a_github_team_workflow.Rmd

  • For the exercise, add all and commit with a comment.

  • For the exercise, switch back and forth between master and test name branches and observe the changes in .Rmd file and R Studio Files pane

  • Switch to the testname branch and check with git branch -a

  • Now it’s time to upload the branch to your repo on GitHub

  1. Create your new branch on GitHub with git push --set-upstream origin branchname where branchname is “testname”
  • This creates the upstream (origin) branch and completes the first push to that branch
  • Now if you refresh your GitHub page you will see the new branch listed under branches

  1. Update your files and push to GitHub as normal
  • You will see the comments on GitHub branch to show how many commits the branch is ahead of the master

3.3 Merging your updates to the Master from a Branch

  1. When ready, merge your updates back with the local master
  • Save and close all files from the branch
  • Execute a final add, commit and push
  • git status should show:
    On branch testname Your branch is up to date with 'origin/testname'.
  • Switch to the master branch with git switch master
  • Ensure your master is up to date with the remote master with git pull
  • Merge the changes from the branch into the master baseline with git merge branchname.
    • This creates a single commit to the local master branch from the branchname history
  • After some messages for the merge, running git status shows:
    On branch master
    Your branch is ahead of 'origin/master' by 3 commits.
    (use "git push" to publish your local commits)
  1. Update your upstream/origin master on GitHub with git push
    • No need to do git add and git commit since the git merge branchname created a commit.

3.4 Deleting a Branch

  1. Deleting the Local and Remote Branch when finished
  • Once all the branch changes have been merged, the branch has is no longer needed
  • It is common to delete branches that are completed from a housekeeping perspective
  • You don’t want to keep reusing a branch for different requirements. Create a new branch
  • Make sure you are not in the branch you want to delete e.g., git switch master
  • Delete a local branch with git branch -d localBranchName
  • Then Delete the remote (origin) branch with git push origin --delete remoteBranchName

4 Team Workflows: Fork & Pull vs. Shared Repos

  • Teams operate from a shared repository or repo
  • Two common models are differentiated by how the team members interact with the shared repo based on their write permissions for the main repo.
  • A large project may have lots of analysts/developers but only a few with write privileges to protect the master branch
    • This often leads to a “Fork and Pull” workflow Model for updates
  • Smaller projects often use a “Shared Repository” Workflow Model where everyone has write privileges
    • Everyone agrees to follow a common process for minimizing merge conflicts.

4.1 Forking and Cloning

  • If you don’t have write privileges to the master you have to create your own copy or Fork of the repo.
  • Forking a repo on GitHub creates a separate copy of the repo on your GitHub account
    • You have write privileges to your forked copy of the repo
  • When you have write privileges to a GitHub repo you can create a local copy by Cloning
  • Cloning a repo on Github creates a local copy of a GitHub repo

4.2 The Fork & Pull Workflow Model

  • In a Fork & Pull workflow model, each user creates a forked version of the repo and then clones the forked repo to their local machine
  • Users make all the changes they want locally (using branching of course)
  • Users push their updates to their forked repo on GitHub
  • Users then initiate a Pull Request to ask the owners of the Original Repo to consider adding the update to the master.
  • This workflow model reduces the amount of friction for new contributors.
  • It is popular with open source projects because people can work independently without upfront coordination without putting the master code baseline at risk.

4.3 The Shared Repository Workflow Model

  • In a shared Repository workflow model, each user clones the shared repo to their local machine
  • The team agrees on who has responsibility for addressing which requirements
  • Users create branches and make all the changes they want locally
  • Before merging with the master however, they should also create a Pull Request with others on the team to initiate code review and general discussion about their changes before the changes are merged into the main development branch.

4.4 Life cycle of a Pull Request

  • Pull Requests initiate discussion about your commits with others.
  • They are tightly integrated with the underlying Git repository so anyone can see exactly what changes would be merged if they accept your request.
  • You can open a Pull Request at any point during the development process:
    • when you have little or no code but want to share some screenshots or general ideas,
    • when you’re stuck and need help or advice, or
    • when you’re ready for someone to review your work.
  • By using GitHub’s @mention system in your Pull Request message, you can ask for feedback from specific people.
    • @GitHub_username anywhere in an issue or pull request notifies the person and subscribes them to future updates.
    • e.g., @rressler - what do you think?
  • Once a Pull Request has been opened, the persons reviewing your changes can enter questions or comments.
  • You can reply as part of the “conversation” about the Pull Request
  • As you get comments you can continue to push updates resolving the comments to your GitHub branch.
  • GitHub will show your new commits and any additional feedback you may receive in the unified Pull Request view.
  • When done you can either merge your code with the final changes or you can close the pull request.

4.5 Life cycle in pictures

  • Go to your branch on GitHub and click on create pull request

  • Make sure you have the pull in the right direction - this one is reverse from normal. Usually the master is on the left and the branch is on the right. Here I am going from an updated master back to a branch.

  • Review your code to ensure you are ready to share and create the Pull Request

  • Write comments for the reviewers and select who you want to review. Team names will pop up.

  • Then click on Create pull request to distribute the request

  • Selecting Pull Requests in the repo will open up the list, When you open a pull request you can select the Files changed to see the diff

  • You can enter comments and submit for all to see

  • When reviewing code you can comment single or multiple lines

  • When the comments are submitted all can see them in the conversation

4.6 After a Pull Request Updates the Baseline, Team Members use Git to Pull and Merge the updates locally

  • Once the baseline Master has been updated with a new merge, each team member should pull the update to their local master, and possible to their local branch.
  • If in doubt about the changes you can use git log to see what has changed - the snapshots
  • By default, with no arguments, git loglists the commits in reverse chronological order i.e., the most recent commits show up first.
  • git log shows each commit with its SHA-1 checksum, the author’s name and email, the date written, and the commit message.
  • To see what is in a commit, you can copy the SHA-1 checksum and use git checkout checksum to move to that commit.
  • BE SURE TO HAVE COMMITTED ALL OF YOUR CURRENT WORK FIRST

5 Final Project Workflow

  • Either model will work for your final group project
  • There are trade-offs between them in terms of level of planning and risk to the code - just like real-world work
  • You have to decide early on as a group which approach to use so individual contributors are using the same method
  • Both require establishing operating rules for the project to protect the working code.
    • Set clear ownership for each requirement and piece of the App or the code - to include the vignette
    • Agree on how the sections of code will interact with each other.
    • Agree on styles, shared variable/object/function names and even libraries to be used.
    • Agree on a testing approach for integrated testing
  • The Shared Repository model requires less collaboration on merging code but puts the app at risk of someone breaking something that was working before (if they skip the pull request).
    • Have to then go back to a working version
    • No need for a final arbiter to approve merge requests - everyone has push rights.
    • Can result in merge conflicts
  • The Fork and Pull Model requires more collaboration for merging code, using pull requests with feedback prior to merging, but can reduce code and team conflicts
    • Tends to drive more use of branching which reduces risk to a working baseline

6 Git and GitHub Summary

  • Branching provides a more sophisticated method for using Git to evolve your analysis without putting working code at much risk
  • Branching allows you to work on multiple items at once in different branches without interfering with each other
  • Branching also sets up the ability to do team workflows for collaborative - not colliding work
  • Small projects usually use a shared repository workflow model
  • Requires collaboration on assignment of elements (or branches) to be worked on
  • Pull requests in GitHub enable conversations about updates across the team before the baseline gets updated.
